\textbf{1.12: The method for solving $au + bv =$gcd$(a,b)$ described in section 1.2 is somewhat inefficient. This exercise describes a method to compute $u$ and $v$ that is well suited for computer implementation. In particular, it uses very little storage.} \\
\bigbreak
\textbf{1.12-a} Show that the following algorithm computes the greatest common divisor $g$ of the positive integers $a$ and $b$, together with a solution $(u,v)$ in integers to the equation $au + bv =$gcd$(a,b)$.\\
\bigbreak
Our code, which was implemented based on the code listed with this problem in the book, shows that the algorithm does successfully compute the greatest common divisor, $g$, as well as $u$ and $v$. This is because it is the extended euclidean algorithm.\\
\bigbreak
\textbf{1.12-b} Implement the above algorithm on a computer using the computer language of your choice.\\
\begin{center}
Please see attached code.\\
\end{center}
\bigbreak
\textbf{1.12-c} Use your program to compute $g=$gcd$(a,b)$ and integer solutions to the equation $au+bv = g$ for the following pairs $(a,b)$.\\
