\textbf{1.23-d} Prove that if gcd$(m,n)=1$, then the pair of congruences $x\equiv a$ (mod$m$) and $x\equiv b$ (mod$n$) has a solution for any choice of $a$ and $b$. Also give an example to show that the condition $gcd(m,n) = 1$ is necessary.\\
\bigbreak
Let $M_{1} = n$ and $M_{2} = m$ \\
$(M_{1},m) = (n,m) =1$, so $M_{1}$ has an inverse ($\exists{M_{1}}^*$ s.t. ${M_{1}}^* \ast M_{1} \equiv 1$ (mod $m$)) \\
$(M_{2},n) = (n,m) =1$, so $M_{2}$ has an inverse ($\exists{M_{2}}^*$ s.t. ${M_{2}}^* \ast M_{2} \equiv 1$ (mod $m$)) \\
If $x= a \ast M_1 \ast {M_{1}}^* + b \ast M_2 \ast {M_{2}}^* \equiv a \ast 1 + b \ast 0 \equiv a$ (mod $m$)\\
If $x= a \ast M_1 \ast {M_{1}}^* + b \ast M_2 \ast {M_{2}}^* \equiv a \ast 0 + b \ast 1 \equiv b$ (mod $n$)\\
\bigbreak
$m \vert M_2 \Leftrightarrow M_2 \equiv 0$ (mod $m$)\\
$n \vert M_1 \Leftrightarrow M_1 \equiv 0$ (mod $n$)\\
${M_{1}}^* \ast M_1 \equiv $ (mod $m$)\\
${M_{2}}^* \ast M_2 \equiv $ (mod $n$)\\
\bigbreak
$gcd(m,n) = 1$ is a necessary condition for the existence of an inverse. If $gcd(m,n)>1$, then $x$ has no multiplicative inverse mod m.\\
